aa(lp16
VBut first, what do we call complexity?
p17
aVWhat is complex?
p18
aVWell, complex is not complicated.
p19
aVSomething complicated comprises many small parts,
p20
aVall different, and each of them
p21
aVhas its own precise role in the machinery.
p22
aVOn the opposite, a complex system
p23
aVis made of many, many similar parts,
p24
aVand it is their interaction
p25
aVthat produces a globally coherent behavior.
p26
aVComplex systems have many interacting parts
p27
aVwhich behave according to simple, individual rules,
p28
aVand this results in emergent properties.
p29
aVThe behavior of the system as a whole
p30
aVcannot be predicted
p31
aVfrom the individual rules only.
p32
aVAs Aristotle wrote,
p33
aVthe whole is greater than the sum of its parts.
p34
aVBut from Aristotle, let's move onto
p35
aVa more concrete example of complex systems.
p36
aa(lp37
VThese are Scottish terriers.
p38
aVIn the beginning, the system is disorganized.
p39
aVThen comes a perturbation: milk.
p40
aVEvery individual starts pushing in one direction
p41
aVand this is what happens.
p42
aVThe pinwheel is an emergent property
p43
aVof the interactions between puppies
p44
aVwhose only rule is to try to keep access to the milk
p45
aVand therefore to push in a random direction.
