aa(lp101
VWhich brings us to bats.
p102
aVBechstein's bats are a common species of European bats.
p103
aVThey are very social animals.
p104
aVMostly they roost, or sleep, together.
p105
aVAnd they live in maternity colonies,
p106
aVwhich means that every spring,
p107
aVthe females meet after the winter hibernation,
p108
aVand they stay together for about six months
p109
aVto rear their young,
p110
aVand they all carry a very small chip,
p111
aVwhich means that every time one of them
p112
aVenters one of these specially equipped bat boxes,
p113
aVwe know where she is,
p114
aVand more importantly,
p115
aVwe know with whom she is.
p116
aVSo I study roosting associations in bats,
p117
aVand this is what it looks like.
p118
aVDuring the day, the bats roost
p119
aVin a number of sub-groups in different boxes.
p120
aVIt could be that on one day,
p121
aVthe colony is split between two boxes,
p122
aVbut on another day,
p123
aVit could be together in a single box,
p124
aVor split between three or more boxes,
p125
aVand that all seems rather erratic, really.
p126
aVIt's called fission-fusion dynamics,
p127
aVthe property for an animal group
p128
aVof regularly splitting and merging
p129
aVinto different subgroups.
p130
aa(lp131
VSo what we do is take all these data
p132
aVfrom all these different days
p133
aVand pool them together
p134
aVto extract a long-term association pattern
p135
aVby applying techniques with network analysis
p136
aVto get a complete picture
p137
aVof the social structure of the colony.
p138
aVOkay? So that's what this picture looks like.
p139
aVIn this network, all the circles
p140
aVare nodes, individual bats,
p141
aVand the lines between them
p142
aVare social bonds, associations between individuals.
p143
aVIt turns out this is a very interesting picture.
p144
aVThis bat colony is organized
p145
aVin two different communities
p146
aVwhich cannot be predicted
p147
aVfrom the daily fission-fusion dynamics.
p148
aVWe call them cryptic social units.
p149
aVEven more interesting, in fact:
p150
aVEvery year, around October,
p151
aVthe colony splits up,
p152
aVand all bats hibernate separately,
p153
aVbut year after year,
p154
aVwhen the bats come together again in the spring,
p155
aVthe communities stay the same.
p156
aa(lp157
VSo these bats remember their friends
p158
aVfor a really long time.
p159
aVWith a brain the size of a peanut,
p160
aVthey maintain individualized,
p161
aVlong-term social bonds,
p162
aVWe didn't know that was possible.
p163
aVWe knew that primates
p164
aVand elephants and dolphins could do that,
p165
aVbut compared to bats, they have huge brains.
p166
aVSo how could it be
p167
aVthat the bats maintain this complex,
p168
aVstable social structure
p169
aVwith such limited cognitive abilities?
p170
aa(lp171
VAnd this is where complexity brings an answer.
p172
aVTo understand this system,
p173
aVwe built a computer model of roosting,
p174
aVbased on simple, individual rules,
p175
aVand simulated thousands and thousands of days
p176
aVin the virtual bat colony.
p177
aVIt's a mathematical model,
p178
aVbut it's not complicated.
p179
aVWhat the model told us is that, in a nutshell,
p180
aVeach bat knows a few other colony members
p181
aVas her friends, and is just slightly more likely
p182
aVto roost in a box with them.
p183
aVSimple, individual rules.
p184
aVThis is all it takes to explain
p185
aVthe social complexity of these bats.
p186
aa(lp187
VBut it gets better.
p188
aVBetween 2010 and 2011,
p189
aVthe colony lost more than two thirds of its members,
p190
aVprobably due to the very cold winter.
p191
aVThe next spring, it didn't form two communities
p192
aVlike every year,
p193
aVwhich may have led the whole colony to die
p194
aVbecause it had become too small.
p195
aVInstead, it formed a single, cohesive social unit,
p196
aVwhich allowed the colony to survive that season
p197
aVand thrive again in the next two years.
p198
aVWhat we know is that the bats
p199
aVare not aware that their colony is doing this.
p200
aVAll they do is follow simple association rules,
p201
aVand from this simplicity
p202
aVemerges social complexity
p203
aVwhich allows the colony to be resilient
p204
aVagainst dramatic changes in the population structure.
