aa(lp207
VNow I want to tell you another story,
p208
aVbut for this we have to travel from Europe
p209
aVto the Kalahari Desert in South Africa.
p210
aVThis is where meerkats live.
p211
aVI'm sure you know meerkats.
p212
aVThey're fascinating creatures.
p213
aVThey live in groups with a very strict social hierarchy.
p214
aVThere is one dominant pair,
p215
aVand many subordinates,
p216
aVsome acting as sentinels,
p217
aVsome acting as babysitters,
p218
aVsome teaching pups, and so on.
p219
aVWhat we do is put very small GPS collars
p220
aVon these animals
p221
aVto study how they move together,
p222
aVand what this has to do with their social structure.
p223
aVAnd there's a very interesting example
p224
aVof collective movement in meerkats.
p225
aVIn the middle of the reserve which they live in
p226
aVlies a road.
p227
aVOn this road there are cars, so it's dangerous.
p228
aVBut the meerkats have to cross it
p229
aVto get from one feeding place to another.
p230
aVSo we asked, how exactly do they do this?
p231
aVWe found that the dominant female
p232
aVis mostly the one who leads the group to the road,
p233
aVbut when it comes to crossing it, crossing the road,
p234
aVshe gives way to the subordinates,
p235
aVa manner of saying,
p236
aV"Go ahead, tell me if it's safe."
p237
aVWhat I didn't know, in fact,
p238
aVwas what rules in their behavior the meerkats follow
p239
aVfor this change at the edge of the group to happen
p240
aVand if simple rules were sufficient to explain it.
p241
aa(lp242
VSo I built a model, a model of simulated meerkats
p243
aVcrossing a simulated road.
p244
aVIt's a simplistic model.
p245
aVMoving meerkats are like random particles
p246
aVwhose unique rule is one of alignment.
p247
aVThey simply move together.
p248
aVWhen these particles get to the road,
p249
aVthey sense some kind of obstacle,
p250
aVand they bounce against it.
p251
aVThe only difference
p252
aVbetween the dominant female, here in red,
p253
aVand the other individuals,
p254
aVis that for her, the height of the obstacle,
p255
aVwhich is in fact the risk perceived from the road,
p256
aVis just slightly higher,
p257
aVand this tiny difference
p258
aVin the individual's rule of movement
p259
aVis sufficient to explain what we observe,
p260
aVthat the dominant female
p261
aVleads her group to the road
p262
aVand then gives way to the others
p263
aVfor them to cross first.
p264
aVGeorge Box, who was an English statistician,
p265
aVonce wrote, "All models are false,
p266
aVbut some models are useful."
p267
aVAnd in fact, this model is obviously false,
p268
aVbecause in reality, meerkats are anything but random particles.
p269
aVBut it's also useful,
p270
aVbecause it tells us that extreme simplicity
p271
aVin movement rules at the individual level
p272
aVcan result in a great deal of complexity
p273
aVat the level of the group.
p274
aVSo again, that's simplifying complexity.
p275
aa(lp276
VI would like to conclude
p277
aVon what this means for the whole species.
p278
aVWhen the dominant female
p279
aVgives way to a subordinate,
p280
aVit's not out of courtesy.
p281
aVIn fact, the dominant female
p282
aVis extremely important for the cohesion of the group.
p283
aVIf she dies on the road, the whole group is at risk.
p284
aVSo this behavior of risk avoidance
p285
aVis a very old evolutionary response.
p286
aVThese meerkats are replicating an evolved tactic
p287
aVthat is thousands of generations old,
p288
aVand they're adapting it to a modern risk,
p289
aVin this case a road built by humans.
p290
aVThey adapt very simple rules,
p291
aVand the resulting complex behavior
p292
aVallows them to resist human encroachment
p293
aVinto their natural habitat.
p294
aa(lp295
VIn the end,
p296
aVit may be bats which change their social structure
p297
aVin response to a population crash,
p298
aVor it may be meerkats
p299
aVwho show a novel adaptation to a human road,
p300
aVor it may be another species.
p301
aVMy message here \u2014 and it's not a complicated one,
p302
aVbut a simple one of wonder and hope \u2014
p303
aVmy message here is that animals
p304
aVshow extraordinary social complexity,
p305
aVand this allows them to adapt
p306
aVand respond to changes in their environment.
p307
aVIn three words, in the animal kingdom,
p308
aVsimplicity leads to complexity
p309
aVwhich leads to resilience.
